I’m trying to use WaitCommand() between 2 other commands. I’ve tried 3 different syntaxes, but each has an error. If I leave it out, “before” and “after” print. the Print method is just System.out.println();

How can I get a delay between two commands?

private void configureBindings() {
m_driverController.b()
.whileTrue(
m_exampleSubsystem.runOnce(() → m_exampleSubsystem.Print(“before”))
//.andThen(()->new WaitCommand(3)) //does not wait
//.andThen(new WaitCommand(3)) //next command does not run
//.andThen(WaitCommand(3)) //“WaitCommand(int) is undefined for the type RobotContainer”
.andThen(m_exampleSubsystem.runOnce(() → m_exampleSubsystem.Print(“after”)))
);
}

Third won’t compile because you’re treating a class name like a method name and that just won’t work like that.

Second one should work, though I suspect you might have something else going on.

Could you share your code as a github link or something instead?

You are sort of close, it needs to look like this:

m_driverController.b()
    .whileTrue(
        m_exampleSubsystem.runOnce(() -> m_exampleSubsystem.Print("before"))
        .andThen(new WaitCommand(3)) 
        .andThen(new WaitCommand(3))    
        .andThen(new WaitCommand(3))      
        .andThen(m_exampleSubsystem.runOnce(() -> m_exampleSubsystem.Print("after")))
    );

The andThen() method returns a sequential command group. So I think your result will be something like:

Seq group 
    -> Print, Seq group
              -> Wait,  Seq group
                        -> Wait,  Seq group
                                  -> Wait,  Seq group
                                            -> Print

If you’re a visual learner, read more here about commands and command groups.

There are a lot of ways to get a delay between two commands. There’s a whole bunch of decorators, you could build the wait into the command itself with a timer, lots of options.

        .andThen(new WaitCommand(3)) 
        .andThen(new WaitCommand(3))    
        .andThen(new WaitCommand(3))

If you can get that to work, work backward from there.

You are running only the Constructor when you say ()->new WaitCommand(). It isn’t a command to run until it’s scheduled.

If you change to .andThen(Commands.waitSeconds(3)) it works as you expect because that’s a Command that can be run. The difference between Runnable and Command.

Sorry - I made a bad reply try again combining my reply and @Oblarg .
You are running the Constructor with .andThen(()->new WaitCommand(3)) //does not wait

You are correct to use .andThen(new WaitCommand(3)) or my alternative but you have to hold the button down because you said while it’s down.
